'''Linda Louise McCartney''' (n<U+00E9>e '''Eastman''', formerly '''See''', September 24, 1941 <U+2013> April 17, 1998) was an American [[photographer]], [[musician]] and [[animal rights]] [[activist]]. She married [[Paul McCartney]] of [[The Beatles]] on March 12, 1969. The McCartneys had four children together: [[Heather McCartney|Heather Louise]] (from her previous marriage, whom Paul McCartney [[adoption|adopted]] in 1969), [[Mary McCartney|Mary Anna]], [[Stella McCartney|Stella Nina]] and [[James McCartney|James Louis]]. Linda became '''Lady McCartney''' when her husband was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in 1997. 

She authored several [[vegetarian]] cookbooks, became a business entrepreneur (starting the Linda McCartney Foods company) and was a professional photographer, publishing ''Linda McCartney's Sixties: Portrait of an Era''. She was a member of [[Wings (band)|Wings]].

McCartney was diagnosed with [[breast cancer]] in 1995, and died at the age of 56 on April 17, 1998 at the McCartney family ranch in [[Tucson, Arizona]]. She left her entire estate to her husband through a Qualified Domestic Trust Fund.<ref name="QDT"/>

==Early years and photography==
[[Image:The Eastman Familyjpeg.jpg|thumb|left|250px|The Eastman family, with Linda Eastman McCartney on the far right.]]
McCartney was born '''Linda Louise Eastman''', the second-eldest of four children, to [[Jewish-American]] parents in [[New York City]]. She had one brother, John (July 10, 1939) and two sisters, Laura (b. 1947) and Louise Jr. (b. 1950).<ref name="ObituaryLindaMcCartney"/><ref name="YoungLinda"/> She grew up in the wealthy [[Scarsdale, New York|Scarsdale]] area of [[Westchester County, New York]] and graduated from [[Scarsdale High School]] in 1960.<ref name="LindaSanFranciscoMuseum">{{cite web |first=d&a, dera and associates, inc. |last= |url=http://www.sfmuseum.org/hist6/lindabio.html |title=Linda McCartney |publisher=The Virtual Museum of San Francisco |accessdate=2008-01-26}}</ref> Her father, [[Lee Eastman]], was the son of Jewish-[[Russian people|Russian]] [[immigration|immigrants]]. He changed his name from Leopold Vail Epstein to Lee Eastman, but was not related to the [[Eastman Kodak]] family.<ref name="YoungLinda">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://www.geocities.com/helenwheels_99/pup.html |title=When I Was A Pup |publisher=Geocities |accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref><ref name="RollingStoneObituary"/> He was songwriter [[Jack Lawrence|Jack Lawrence's]] attorney, and at his request, Lawrence wrote a song called, "[[Linda (1946 song)|Linda]]", in honour of the five-year-old, which was recorded by [[Buddy Clark]] in 1947.<ref name="YoungLinda"/> Her mother was [[Louise Linder|Louise Sara Lindner Eastman]]<U+2014>heiress to the Lindner Department Store fortune<U+2014>who died in the crash of [[American Airlines Flight 1]] in [[Queens, New York]], in 1962.<ref name="LindnerAirCrash">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19620301-0 |title=Accident description |publisher=Aviation Safety Network  |date=1996|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref><ref name="McCartneysLunch">{{cite web |first=Nigel |last=Slater |url=http://shopping.guardian.co.uk/food/story/0,,2068978,00.html |title=When the McCartneys came for lunch |publisher=[[The Guardian]] |date=[[2007-04-29]]|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref> McCartney later said that because of her mother's death, she hated travelling in airplanes.<ref name="BrainyLindaQuote"/> McCartney studied for a [[Fine Art]] major at the [[University of Arizona]].<ref name="LindaSanFranciscoMuseum"/> Her first marriage was to John Melvin See Jr., whom she met at college. They married on June 18, 1962, and their daughter [[Heather McCartney|Heather Louise]] was born on December 31, 1962. They were [[divorce]]d in June 1965. McCartney later commented that See was a "nice man, a [[geology|geologist]], an [[Ernest Hemingway]] type".<ref name="BrainyLindaQuote"/> (See committed suicide with a self-inflicted gunshot wound on March 19, 2000, at his home in [[Tucson]]).<ref name="StartingOver">{{cite web |first=Jill |last=Smolowe |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20130865,00.html |title=Starting Over |publisher=PEOPLE (Time Inc) |date=[[2000-03-03]] |accessdate=2008-07-27}}</ref>  

McCartney started work as a receptionist for the ''[[Town & Country (magazine)|Town & Country]]'' magazine, and was the only unofficial photographer on board the ''SS Sea Panther'' yacht on the [[Hudson River]] who was allowed to take photographs of [[The Rolling Stones]] during a record promotion party.<ref name="RollingStoneObituary"/><ref name="StonesYachtPhoto">{{cite web |first=Linda |last=McCartney |url=http://www.ackland.org/art/exhibitions/mccartney/b.html |title=The Rolling Stones aboard SS Panther on the Hudson, 1966 |publisher=The Estate of Linda McCartney |accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref><ref name="FieldsBiogChapter1">{{cite web |first=Danny |last=Fields |url=http://www.wingspan.ru/bookseng/linda/01.html |title=Linda McCartney <U+201C>The Biography<U+201D> Chapter 1 |publisher=Wingspan Russia |accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref> Although she had previously only studied the photography of [[horse]]s in [[Arizona]] at an arts centre with a teacher, Hazel Archer, she was asked to be the house photographer at the [[Fillmore East]] concert hall.<ref name="FieldsBiogChapter2">{{cite web |first=Danny |last=Fields |url=http://www.wingspan.ru/bookseng/linda/02.html |title=Linda McCartney <U+201C>The Biography<U+201D> Chapter 2 |publisher=Wingspan Russia |accessdate=2008-02-01}}</ref> She photographed artists such as [[Aretha Franklin]], [[Jimi Hendrix]], [[Bob Dylan]], [[Janis Joplin]], [[Eric Clapton]], [[Simon and Garfunkel]], [[The Who]], and [[The Doors]].<ref name="LightFromWithin"/><ref name="FranklinPhoto">{{cite web |first=Linda |last=McCartney|url=http://www.ackland.org/art/exhibitions/mccartney/e.html |title=Aretha Franklin - black and white photograph |publisher=The Estate of Linda McCartney |accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref> She photographed Clapton for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine, becoming the first woman to have a photo featured on the front cover (May 11, 1968).  McCartney and her husband also appeared on the cover of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' on January 31, 1974, making her the only person both to have taken a photo for and to have been photographed for the magazine cover.<ref name="RollingStoneObituary"/> Her photographs were later exhibited in more than 50 galleries internationally, as well as at the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] in [[London]].<ref name="RollingStoneObituary"/> A collection of photographs from that time, ''Linda McCartney's Sixties: Portrait of an Era'', was published in 1993.<ref name="LightFromWithin">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://archer2000.tripod.com/lindaremembered/wingsphotos.html |title=Light From Within |publisher=Archer & Valerie Productions/MPL Communications, Ltd. |date=2001|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref><ref name="SixtiesPortraitBook">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://www.amazon.com/Linda-McCartneys-Sixties-Portrait-Era/dp/082122056X/ref=pd_bbs_sr_1?ie=UTF8&s=books&qid=1201487438&sr=1-1 |title=Linda McCartney's Sixties: Portrait of an Era |publisher=Amazon |accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref>

==Paul McCartney==
{{see|Paul McCartney}}
On May 15, 1967, the then Linda Eastman met Paul McCartney at a [[Georgie Fame]] concert at [[the Bag O'Nails]] club in London.<ref name="AbracadabraBeatleHomes">{{cite web |first=Raymond |last=Newman |url=http://www.revolverbook.co.uk/beatleslondon.html |title=The Beatles' London, 1965-66 |publisher=Abracadabra |accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref> She was in the UK on an assignment to take photographs of "Swinging Sixties" musicians in London. The two later went to the Speakeasy club on Margaret Street to see [[Procol Harum]].<ref name="McCartneysLunch"/><ref name="DeepPurpleAtlas">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://www.deep-purple.net/archive/a-z/speakeasy/48-Margaret-St-resizes.jpg |title=48 Margaret Street, London |publisher=The Deep Purple Appreciation Society |accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref>  They met again four days later at the launch party for ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'' at [[Brian Epstein]]'s house in [[Belgravia]].  When Eastman's assignment was completed, she flew back to [[New York City]].<ref name="MilesPage117"> Miles 1998. p117.</ref> In May 1968, they met again in [[New York]], as [[John Lennon]] and Paul McCartney were there to announce the formation of [[Apple Records|Apple Corps]].<ref name="Spitzp761"> Spitz 2005. p761.</ref> In September of the same year, McCartney phoned her and asked her to fly over to London.  They were married six months later at a small civil ceremony (when she was four months [[pregnant]] with their daughter [[Mary McCartney|Mary]]) at [[Marylebone]] Registry Office on March 12, 1969.<ref name="OnThisDayBBC">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/march/12/newsid_3607000/3607215.stm |title=1969: Paul McCartney weds Linda Eastman |publisher=[[BBC]] |accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref><ref name="Sequel">{{cite news |title=Sequel: All Together Now. Thirty years later, the surviving Beatles get back to where they once belonged | work=People | date=February 14, 1994 | accessdate=2006-11-10 | language=English }}</ref> She said after the birth of James that four children was enough.<ref name="BrainyLindaQuote"/> She became Lady McCartney when her husband was knighted in 1997.<ref name="RollingStoneObituary"/> Her brother, entertainment lawyer John Eastman, has represented Paul McCartney since the break-up of The Beatles..<ref name="LindasBrotherJohn">{{cite web |first=Brigham T |last=Barnes |url=http://www.law.nyu.edu/newscalendars/2004_2005/roundtable/eastman.html |title=Entertainment lawyer John Eastman (64) discussed "doing something different,"  |publisher=New York School of Law |date=[[2004-09-30]]|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref> Linda McCartney now has six [[Family|grandchildren]], all of which were born after her death: Mary's three sons Arthur Alistair Donald (born April 3, 1999), Elliot Donald (born August 1, 2002), and Sam Aboud (born August 11, 2008), and Stella's children, Miller Alasdhair James Willis (born February 25, 2005),<ref>[http://marriage.about.com/od/entertainmen1/p/paulmccartney.htm  Sir Paul and Lady Heather McCartney Marriage Profile] Retrieved: 29 January 2007 </ref> daughter Bailey Linda Olwyn Willis (born December 8, 2006),<ref> [http://www.teengossipblog.com/teengossipblog/teengossipblog.php/2006/12/13/stella_mccartney_has_a_baby_girl  Stella McCartney has a baby girl] Retrieved: 27 January 2007</ref> and Beckett Robert Lee Willis (born January 8, 2008).
===Music===
{{main|Wings (band)}}
[[Image:Paul and Linda McCartney.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Paul and Linda McCartney at the 1974 Academy Awards.]]
Linda made an uncredited vocal contribution to the Beatles' [[Let It Be (song)|title song]] of ''[[Let It Be (album)|Let It Be]]'' in January 1969.<ref name="RollingStoneInterview">{{cite web |first=Paul |last=Gambaccini |url= http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/paulmccartney/articles/story/9359339/the_rs_interview_paul_mccartney?source=paulmccartney_rssfeed |title=The Rolling Stone Interview: Paul McCartney |publisher= |date=[[1974-01-31]]|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref> After the breakup of the Beatles in 1970, McCartney taught her to play keyboards, and permanently included her in the lineup for his new group Wings.<ref name="McCartneyWingsIt">{{cite web |first=Ray |last=Bonici |url=http://beatles.ncf.ca/mpl.html |title=Paul McCartney Wings it alone |publisher=Music Express" (Canada)  issue #56 (GG70470)  |date=1982|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref> The group garnered several [[Grammy Awards]], becoming one of the most successful bands of the 1970s, but had to endure jibes like, "What do you call a [[cow]] with wings? Linda McCartney".<ref name="GermaineGreerPopBitch">{{cite web |first=Germaine |last=Greer |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/germaine-greer-pop-bitch-479025.html |title=Germaine Greer: Pop bitch |publisher=The Independent |date=[[2006-05-21]]|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref> Linda later admitted that the early accusations about her singing out of tune in the early days with Wings were true.<ref name="BrainyLindaQuote"/> 

In 1977, a single entitled "Seaside Woman" was released by an obscure band called [[Suzy and the Red Stripes]], on [[Epic Records]] in the U.S.<ref name="RollingStoneInterview"/> In reality, Suzy and the Red Stripes were Wings with Linda McCartney (who also wrote the song) on lead vocals.<ref name="SuzyRedStripes">{{cite web |first=Graham |last=Calkin |url=http://www.jpgr.co.uk/col_ams7461.html |title=Seaside Woman   b/w   B-Side To Seaside |publisher=Graham Calkin's Beatles Pages |accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref> The song was recorded by Wings in 1972, in response to a lawsuit by [[Associated TeleVision|ATV]] (which owned [[Northern Songs]]) over Paul McCartney's practice of granting his wife co-writing credit on his songs, which had the effect of transferring a share of the publishing royalties to [[MPL Communications]] from ATV.  The lawsuit was [[legal settlement|settled out of court]].<ref name="RollingStoneInterview"/>

McCartney and her husband shared an Oscar nomination for the song "Live and Let Die", which they co-wrote.<ref name="RollingStoneObituary"/> Linda McCartney's album ''[[Wide Prairie]]'', which included "Seaside Woman", was released posthumously in 1998.<ref name="ReleaseOfAlbum">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/163837.stm |title=Linda's lone effort to be released |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=[[1998-09-03]]|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref> Paul McCartney worked with the help of the Beatles' engineer, [[Geoff Emerick]], to finish the album.<ref name="WidePrairie">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://archer2000.tripod.com/lindaremembered/prairie2.html |title=Wide Prairie |publisher=2000 Archer & Valerie Productions |date=2007|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref> Along with eight other [[British people|British]] composers, he contributed to the choral album ''[[A Garland for Linda]]'', and dedicated his [[classical music|classical]] album, ''[[Ecce Cor Meum]]'', to his late wife.<ref name="GarlandForLindaBBC">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/345875.stm |title=A Garland for Linda |publisher=[[BBC]]|date=[[1999-05-17]]|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref> In January 1999, "The Light Comes From Within" single from the ''Wide Prairie'' album was banned by TV and radio stations in the UK. Paul McCartney placed advertisements in English national newspapers asking parents to give "guidance" as to whether their children could be "morally corrupted" by the song lyrics, which included the lines, "You say I'm simple, you say I'm a hick, You're fucking no-one, you stupid dick".<ref name="LindaSongBanned">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/262450.stm |title=Linda's last song 'banned' |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=[[1999-01-25]]|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref>

==Vegetarianism, activism and lifestyle==
McCartney introduced her husband to [[vegetarianism]] in 1975, and promoted a vegetarian diet through her cookbooks: ''Linda McCartney<U+2019>s Home Cooking'' (1989) ''Linda<U+2019>s Kitchen'' and ''Simple and Inspiring Recipes for Meatless Meals''. She explained her change to vegetarianism by saying that she did not "eat anything with a face", and if "[[slaughterhouses]] had glass walls the whole world would be vegetarian".<ref name="ObituaryLindaMcCartney">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/80494.stm |title=Obituary: Linda McCartney  |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=[[1998-04-19]]|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref><ref name="BrainyLindaQuote">{{cite web |first=Linda |last=McCartney |url=http://www.brainyquote.com/quotes/authors/l/linda_mccartney.html |title=Linda McCartney Quotes |publisher=Brainy Media |accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref> In 1991, she introduced a line of frozen vegetarian meals under the Linda McCartney Foods name, which made her wealthy independently of her husband.<ref name="LindaFoods">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://www.linda-mccartney.com/about-us/linda.php |title=About Linda |publisher=The Hain Celestial Group, Inc |date=2007|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref> In 1995, McCartney appeared in animated form with her husband in ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode "[[Lisa the Vegetarian]]". The "[[Trash of the Titans]]" episode was dedicated to her memory. The [[H. J. Heinz Company]] acquired Linda McCartney Foods in March 2000, and the [[Hain Celestial Group]] bought it in 2007.<ref name="McCartneysLunch"/><ref name="LindaRemembered"/>

McCartney was a strong advocate for [[animal rights]], and lent her support to many organizations like [[PETA]] (People For The Ethical Treatment of Animals) as well as [[Campaign to Protect Rural England|The Council For The Protection of Rural England]], [[Friends Of The Earth]], and was a patron of the [[League Against Cruel Sports]].<ref name="McCartneysLunch"/> Before her death, she narrated a TV advertisement for PETA, in which she said: "Have you ever seen a [[fish]] gasping for breath when you take it out of the water? They<U+2019>re saying, <U+2018>Thanks a lot for killing me. It feels great, you know.<U+2019> No! It hurts!"<ref name="FishingHurts">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://www.fishinghurts.com/feat/linda/ |title=PETA<U+2019>s Fish Empathy Ad Hits the Airwaves  |publisher=Fishing Hurts |accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref> After her death, PETA created the Linda McCartney Memorial Award.<ref name="LindaRemembered">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://archer2000.tripod.com/lindaremembered/lindabio.html |title=Linda McCartney Remembered |publisher=Archer & Valerie Productions |date=1998-2008|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref>

McCartney was arrested in [[Los Angeles]] for possession of [[marijuana]] in 1975, although all charges were later dropped.<ref name="PoBustShocker">{{cite web |first=Harry |last=Wasserman |url=http://www.taima.org/en/hemplib3.htm#mccartney |title=Paul's Pot-Bust Shocker Makes Him A Jailhouse Rocker |publisher=High Times |date=[[1980-07-06]]|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref> In 1984, the McCartneys were arrested in [[Barbados]] for possession of marijuana and were fined $100 each. They flew to [[Heathrow Airport]], London, where Linda McCartney was arrested again on charges of possession. She later commented that hard drugs were disgusting, but marijuana "is pretty lightweight".<ref name="BrainyLindaQuote"/><ref name="ArrestedCNN">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,954120,00.html |title=Arrested: Paul McCartney |publisher=[[Time Magazine]] |date=[[1984-01-30]]|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref><ref name="McCartneyOnDrugs">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://www.10zenmonkeys.com/2007/01/03/paul-mccartney-on-drugs/ |title=Paul McCartney On Drugs |publisher=10 Zen Monkeys |accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref>

==Death==
[[Image:Linda Eastman McCartney.jpg|thumb|left|150px|A photo of Linda McCartney shortly before her death.]] 
McCartney was diagnosed with breast cancer in 1995, and her condition soon grew worse as it spread to her [[liver]].<ref name="RollingStoneObituary"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Saffian, Sarah |title=Untimely deaths haunt extended Beatles family | work=US Magazine Company |page=37 |date=December 17, 2001 | accessdate=2006-11-10 }}</ref> Paul's last words to her were: "You're up on your beautiful [[Appaloosa]] stallion. It's a fine spring day. We're riding through the woods. The [[Common Bluebell|bluebells]] are all out, and the sky is clear-blue".<ref name="LindaRemembered"/> Linda McCartney died at age 56 on April 17, 1998, at the McCartney family ranch in Tucson, Arizona.<ref name="RollingStoneObituary">{{cite web |first=Richard |last=Skanse |url=http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/wings/articles/story/5926813/linda_mccartney_dies_at_56 |title=Linda McCartney Dies at 56  |publisher=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=[[1998-04-20]]|accessdate=2008-01-26}}</ref> She was [[cremation|cremated]] in Tucson, and her ashes were scattered at McCartney's farm in [[Sussex]].<ref name="SuicideClaims">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/82362.stm |title=Linda McCartney suicide claims dismissed|publisher=[[BBC]] |date=[[1998-04-23]]|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref> Paul later suggested that fans remember her by donating to breast cancer research charities that do not support [[animal testing]], "or the best tribute &mdash; go veggie".<ref name="RollingStoneObituary"/> Memorial services were held for her at [[St. Martin-in-the-Fields]] in London, which was attended by [[George Harrison]], [[David Gilmour]] and [[Ringo Starr]]. A memorial service was also held at [[Riverside Church]] in [[Manhattan]], two months after her death.<ref name="LindaRemembered"/> 

Talking later about the medication used to treat her breast cancer, Paul said: "If a drug has got to be used on humans then legally it has to be finally tested on an animal ... This was difficult for Linda when she was undergoing her treatment."<ref name="BBC">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/199457.stm |title= Paul's dilemma over animal testing |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=[[1998-10-23]]|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref> He also claimed that she was unsure if the drugs she took had been tested on animals: "During the treatment, a nice answer is a nice answer and if they (the doctors) say, `It's OK to have this because we didn't test it on animals', you are going to believe them."<ref name="BBC"/> She left her entire fortune to her husband in a special [[trust (law)|trust]], known as a Qualified Domestic Trust, which allows deferral of estate taxes due on her assets until after his death.<ref name="QDT">{{cite web |first=Stephen C. |last=Gruber |url=http://www.ca-trusts.com/qdt.html |title=Qualified Domestic Trust (QDT) Living Trusts for Non-Citizens |publisher=Stephen C. Gruber, Attorney at Law |accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref><ref name="FortuneForPaul">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/676911.stm |title=Linda leaves fortune to Paul |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=[[2000-03-14]]|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref> He will have access to any [[royalties]] from books, records and any financial remuneration for the use of his wife's photographs.<ref name="LindasLastWill">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://www.courttv.com/people/wills/McCartney.html |title=The Will of Linda McCartney  |publisher=2007 Courtroom Television Network LLC |date=[[1996-07-04]]|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref> He has pledged to continue her line of vegetarian food, and to keep it free from [[genetically modified organism]]s.<ref name="GMFoodPledge">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/365947.stm |title=Sir Paul's GM foods pledge  |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=[[1999-06-10]]|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref>

''Wide Prairie'', a six-minute cartoon [[fantasy]] film by Linda McCartney and director Oscar Grillo, was premi<U+00E8>red at the [[Edinburgh International Film Festival]] on August 19, 1998. It was shown before the British premi<U+00E8>re of ''[[The Horse Whisperer]]'', starring [[Robert Redford]].<ref name="AnimatedFilmGrillo">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/133448.stm |title=Linda McCartney's last film set for premiere  |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=[[1998-08-16]]|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref><ref name="CartoonFilm">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/154741.stm |title=Linda's last film premi<U+00E8>res to packed house  |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=[[1998-08-20]]|accessdate=2008-01-30}}</ref> On April 10, 1999, Paul McCartney performed at the tribute "Concert for Linda" in the [[Royal Albert Hall]], with numerous artists including [[George Michael]], [[the Pretenders]], [[Elvis Costello]] and [[Tom Jones (singer)|Tom Jones]].<ref name="AlbertHallConcert">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/316419.stm |title=Paul McCartney leads Linda tribute  |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=[[1999-04-11]]|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref> In January 2000, he announced donations in excess of $2,000,000 for cancer research at the [[Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center]] in New York and the Arizona Cancer Center in Tucson, where Linda received treatment. The centers received [[$]]1 million ([[<U+00A3>]]625,000) each. The donations, through the Garland Appeal, were made on the condition no animals would be used for testing purposes.<ref name="LindaRemembered"/><ref name="MoneyCancerResearch">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/591591.stm |title=Sir Paul's $2m cancer donation  |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=[[2000-01-05]]|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref> In 2000, The Linda McCartney Centre, a cancer clinic, opened at [[Royal Liverpool University Hospital|The Royal Liverpool University Hospital]].<ref name="LindaRemembered"/> In November 2002, the Linda McCartney Kintyre Memorial Trust opened a memorial garden in [[Campbeltown]] &mdash; the main town on the [[Mull of Kintyre]] &mdash; with the dedication of a [[bronze]] statue of Linda by sculptor [[Jane Robbins (sculptor)|Jane Robbins]], commissioned and donated by Paul.<ref name="LindaRemembered"/><ref name="Kintyre">{{cite web |first= |last= |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/2384099.stm |title=Scots tribute to Linda McCartney |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=[[2002-11-01]]|accessdate=2008-01-28}}</ref>

==Portrayals on screen==
[[Elizabeth Mitchell (actress)|Elizabeth Mitchell]] and Gary Bakewell played Linda and Paul McCartney in the 2000 TV movie ''The Linda McCartney Story''..<ref>http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0240683/ IMDb entry for ''The Linda McCartney Story''</ref> Catherine Strauss had earlier played her (as "Linda Eastman") in the 1985 TV movie ''John and Yoko: A Love Story''.<ref>http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0089380/ IMDb entry for ''John and Yoko: A Love Story''</ref> Tamara Blum Cohen appeared as Linda McCartney in a 2007 episode of the TV series ''[[Final 24]]'' focused on [[Keith Moon]].<ref>http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1151590/ IMDb entry for ''Final 24'' episode "Keith Moon"</ref>

